What is PWM?

PWM (Pulse Width Modulation) is a technique that simulates analog output by rapidly switching a digital pin ON and OFF. By changing the ON time (duty cycle), Arduino controls the average power delivered to a device.

Why is PWM used?

To control LED brightness.
To control DC motor speed.
To save power while providing variable output.
Practical IoT Example of analogRead()

Smart Street Light

An LDR (Light Dependent Resistor) is connected to an analog pin.
Arduino uses analogRead() to measure ambient light.
If it gets dark, the street light turns ON automatically.
Practical IoT Example of analogWrite()

Smart Home Lighting

An LED is connected to a PWM pin.
Arduino uses analogWrite() to adjust the LED brightness based on room conditions or commands from a mobile app.
